Q1: Web scraping

bike_website <- read_html("https://www.citibikenyc.com/pricing")
Plan <- bike_website %>%
  html_elements("h2") %>%
  html_text()
Plan <- Plan[1:3]
Pricing <- bike_website %>%
  html_elements(".type-alpha--m") %>%
  html_text()
Minutes <- bike_website %>%
  html_elements(".spacing--half .type-alpha--s") %>%
  html_text()

Q2: Critique

The goal of the analysis was to study the different riding behaviors by age groups. I think that there was an incorrect decision in not having enough age groups and should have instead separated the ages by 0-16, 17-20, 21-25, 26-30, 31-40, 41-50, 51-60, 61+. The reasoning behind this was the age 0-16 are still dependent on their parents and therefore it makes reasonable sense to keep it this way. 17-20 is the age where people are considered teenagers and they have more agency and independence and thus more likely to use the bikes more. 20-25, this is an age where they are becoming adults. I split the twenties into 2 as they age and more people are more likely to get other modes of transport as they age. 31-40, 41-50, 51-60 I split into a decade as their lives have become more stable and may have kids and this need less use of the bikes. At the age of 60+ it is unlikely for the elderly to be riding bikes in nyc.

There is another Critique that the age group between 0 to 14 is incorrect because. It is Prohibited for a person to be riding a bike if they are under 16 years of age. So therefore the age group should be 0 to 16.

The Rules are stated here in Prohibited Acts.

Q3: Polishing

nycbikes18_raw <- read_csv("data/2018-citibike-tripdata.csv")
nycbikes18 <- filter(nycbikes18_raw, birth_year > 1900) %>% mutate(gender = case_when(gender == 0 ~ "Unknown", gender == 1 ~ "Male", gender == 2 ~ "Female"))
p1 <- ggplot(nycbikes18, aes(gender, fill = usertype)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
  labs(x = "Gender", y = "Number of Users", fill = "Usertype") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Dark2") +
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("Riding behaviours of different genders based on their user types")
p1

Q4: Exploration

There are 3 objectives:

Objective 1

The first is to see which station has the most bikes to see where it is the most used and where we should add more bikes.

no_bike_trips_location <- nycbikes18 %>%
  select(start_station_name, bikeid) %>%
  group_by(start_station_name) %>%
  summarise(no_of_bikes_trips = n()) %>%
  filter(no_of_bikes_trips > 0) %>%
  arrange(no_of_bikes_trips)
no_bike_trips_location

p2 <- no_bike_trips_location %>%
  mutate(start_station_name = fct_reorder(start_station_name, no_of_bikes_trips)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(start_station_name, no_of_bikes_trips, fill = start_station_name)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90), legend.position = "none") +
  labs(y = "Number of Bikes Trips", x = "Starting Location")
p2

The most popular place for a journey to start is at Grove St Path. This means that we should be hyper aware of when there are no more bikes left and when it needs to be repopulated. The most suitable times to be hyper aware and to check are shown in Assignment 2 Question 10. For weekdays we look at Subscribers and for weekends we look at Customers for when the bikes need to be replenished.

Objective 2

The second is to check how long the top 50 bikes has been ridden on to check whether we need to replace it or need to check for maintenance.

trip_duration <- nycbikes18 %>%
  select(bikeid, tripduration) %>%
  group_by(bikeid) %>%
  summarise(time = round(sum(tripduration) / 60 / 60)) %>%
  arrange(desc(time)) %>%
  slice(1:50)
trip_duration
#> # A tibble: 50 x 2
#>    bikeid  time

p3 <- trip_duration %>%
  mutate(bikeid = as_factor(bikeid)) %>%
  mutate(bikeid = fct_reorder(bikeid, time)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(bikeid, time)) +
  geom_col() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90)) +
  labs(x = "Bike ID", y = "Time in Hours")
p3

Bikes that have 300 hours should be checked for maintenance and to see if it needs to be replaced.

Objective 3

The 3rd is to check when is there the most customers interest and how would we be able to provide more amenities so that we are able to attract more tourists. I have used other sources such as Google trends to see if the interest in the number of searches corresponds to the number of customers that are cycling during the same time. And to see if the amount searched and the number that was ridden have the same rates.

customer_rides <- nycbikes18 %>%
  mutate(week = week(starttime)) %>%
  filter(usertype %in% "Customer") %>%
  group_by(week) %>%
  summarise(week, no_of_rides = n()) %>%
  distinct()
customer_rides

p4 <- ggplot() +
  geom_line(data = customer_rides, aes(week, no_of_rides), size = 1, color = "Blue") +
  ggtitle("Number of Rides in a Year - Tourists") +
  labs(x = "Weeks within a Year", y = "Number of Rides")

p5 <- ggplot() +
  geom_line(data = google_search, aes(weekid, no_search), size = 1, color = "Red") +
  ggtitle("Google Searches in a Year - Tourists") +
  labs(x = "Weeks within a Year", y = "Number of Searches")

p6 <- p5 + p4
p6

As you can see the rate of searches coincides with the rate of rides. If we are able to optimize our marketing and the search engine using SEO. Then there should be an increase with the number of tourists riding Citi Bikes.

What I have learned

  • I have learned that I should not super-impose data (as shown in appendix) and have a dual Y charts as that is bad practice and it can be misleading. More information here.
  • Some other things to point out is whether the objectives are asking the right questions so that Citi Bikes can be a more profitable company.
